{"title_page": "Urziceni", "text_new": "{{For|the commune in Satu Mare County|Urziceni, Satu Mare}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Ialomi\u021ba\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Ialomi\u021ba County\n|image_skyline = Urziceni BO.jpg\n|image_caption = The Orthodox church in the city center\n|official_name=Urziceni\n|image_map              = Urziceni in the Ialomi\u021ba County.svg\n|image_shield=ROU IL Urziceni CoA.jpg\n|leader_name=Constantin Sava\n|website= {{url|http://primaria-urziceni.ro/}}\n|leader_party=PNL\n|area_total_km2=53.57\n|coordinates   = {{coord|44|43|5|N|26|38|43|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Urziceni''' ({{IPA-ro|urzi\u02c8t\u0361\u0283en\u02b2}}) is a [[municipiu|city]] in [[Ialomi\u021ba County]], [[Romania]], located around 60&nbsp;km north-east of [[Bucharest]]. It has a population of 14,053: 93.1% [[Romanians]],  4.6% [[Roma in Romania|Roma]] and 1.6% [[Hungarians]].\n\n==Demographics==\n\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n| align = none\n| cols = 2\n|1912 |3437\n|1930 |8616\n|1948 |4425\n|1956 |6061\n|1966 |9291\n|1977 |12476\n|1992 |19483\n|2002 |19088\n|2011 |14053\n}}\n\nAs the census of 2011 results shows, Urziceni is ranked in 3rd place in [[Ialomi\u021ba County]], after [[Slobozia]] and [[Fete\u0219ti]] with 14053 stable residents, there are  6765 [[male]]s and 7288 [[female]]s. <!-- Source = census data -->\n\n==Origins==\n\nFounded by [[Romanians|Romanian]] shepherds, its name is derived from the word \"urzic\u0103\" ([[Urtica|nettle]]). It was mentioned for the first time in a written document on 23 April 1596, during the reign of [[Mihai Viteazul]]. It gained in 1831 the status of [[market town]] and in 1895 the city status. For 117 years, it was the capital of Ialomi\u0163a county (between 1716 and 1833).\n\n==Soccer Record==\nA little town by any standards, Urziceni is perhaps best known for its [[Association football|football]] team, [[FC Unirea Urziceni|Unirea Urziceni]]. Urziceni holds the record for the smallest town to have a team in the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] after [[Fontvieille, Monaco|Fontvieille]], hometown of [[AS Monaco FC]]. The team wound up a year later.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Urziceni}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061114193004/http://www.urziceni.ro/ Urziceni.ro]\n* [http://www.mesageruldeurziceni.ro/ Mesagerul de Urziceni]\n\n{{Ialomi\u0163a County}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Ialomi\u021ba County]]\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n\n\n{{Ialomi\u0163a-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|the commune in Satu Mare County|Urziceni, Satu Mare}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Ialomi\u021ba\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Ialomi\u021ba County\n|image_skyline = Urziceni BO.jpg\n|image_caption = The Orthodox church in the city center\n|official_name=Urziceni\n|image_map              = Urziceni in the Ialomi\u021ba County.svg\n|image_shield=ROU IL Urziceni CoA.jpg\n|leader_name=Constantin Sava\n|website= {{url|http://primaria-urziceni.ro/}}\n|leader_party=PNL\n|area_total_km2=53.57\n|coordinates   = {{coord|44|43|5|N|26|38|43|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Urziceni''' ({{IPA-ro|urzi\u02c8t\u0361\u0283en\u02b2}}) is a [[municipiu|city]] in [[Ialomi\u021ba County]], [[Romania]], located around 60&nbsp;km north-east of [[Bucharest]]. It has a population of 14,053: 93.1% [[Romanians]],  4.6% [[Roma in Romania|Roma]] and 1.6% [[Hungarians]].\n\n==Demographics==\n\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n| align = none\n| cols = 2\n|1912 |3437\n|1930 |8616\n|1948 |4425\n|1956 |6061\n|1966 |9291\n|1977 |12476\n|1992 |19483\n|2002 |19088\n|2011 |14053\n}}\n\nAs the census of 2011 results shows, Urziceni is ranked in 3rd place in [[Ialomi\u021ba County]], after [[Slobozia]] and [[Fete\u0219ti]] with 14053 stable residents, there are  6765 [[male]]s and 7288 [[female]]s. <!-- Source = census data -->\n\n==Origins==\n\nFounded by [[Romanians|Romanian]] shepherds, its name is derived from the word \"urzic\u0103\" ([[Urtica|nettle]]). It was mentioned for the first time in a written document on 23 April 1596, during the reign of [[Mihai Viteazul]]. It gained in 1831 the status of [[market town]] and in 1895 the city status. For 117 years, it was the capital of Ialomi\u0163a county (between 1716 and 1833).\n\n==Soccer Record==\nA little town by any standards, Urziceni is perhaps best known for its [[Association football|football]] team, [[FC Unirea Urziceni|Unirea Urziceni]]. Urziceni holds the record for the smallest town to have a team in the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] after [[Fontvieille, Monaco|Fontvieille]], hometown of [[AS Monaco FC]]. The team wound up a year later.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Urziceni}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061114193004/http://www.urziceni.ro/ Urziceni.ro]\n* [http://www.mesageruldeurziceni.ro/ Mesagerul de Urziceni]\n\n{{Ialomi\u0163a County}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Ialomi\u021ba County]]\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n\n{{Ialomi\u0163a-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Urziceni"}
{"title_page": "Turtle's Progress", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox television|\n  | show_name = Turtle's Progress\n  | image =\n  | runtime = 60 minutes\n  | creator = Edmund Ward\n  | producer = Nicholas Palmer\n  | starring  = [[John F. Landry]]<br>[[Michael Attwell]]<br>[[Paul Shane]]\n  | country = United Kingdom\n  | network = [[Associated TeleVision|ATV]] ([[ITV (TV network)|ITV]])\n  | first_aired = 23 April 1979\n  | last_aired = 4 July 1980\n  | num_episodes = 13\n  |}}\n\n'''''Turtle's Progress''''' is a [[British television]] series broadcast between 1979 and 1980.  The offbeat humour of the show attracted a small but cult audience, and the show only ran for two series.\n\n==Background==\nThe character of Turtle had first appeared in 1975 in \"[[The Hanged Man (TV series)|The Hanged Man]]\", also created by Edmund Ward.\n\n==Plot==\nThe series was an ITV ATV Drama, and dealt with a petty criminal named Turtle (played by [[John F. Landry]]) and his minder, \"Razor\" Eddie ([[Michael Attwell]]), who by accident come into possession of the proceeds of a major bank robbery. Eddie had been told to steal a van, and the van he stole turned out to be the getaway vehicle for the robbery. Inside were a large number of safe deposit boxes.\n\nEach episode of the show dealt with Turtle and Eddie opening one box and dealing with the contents of it.\n\nPart of the humour came from the interplay between Turtle and Superintendent Rafferty, who knew they did the crime, had no evidence on which to act, but lurked about in hope of a break.\n\nIn early 2011 the entire series was released on DVD by Networkdvd.co.uk.\n\n==Cast==\n[[John F. Landry]] - Turtle<br>\n[[Michael Attwell]] - Razor Eddie Malone<br>\nRuby Head - Aunt Ethel Wagstaff<br>\nTony London - George Wagstaff<br>\n[[James Grout]] - Superintendent Rafferty (Series 1 only)<br>\n[[David Swift (actor)|David Swift]] - Superintendent Rafferty (Series 2 only)<br>\n[[Tony Melody]] - Colour Sergeant Arnold<br>\n[[Leueen Willoughby]] - Miss Anthea Goodliff\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0078707|title=Turtle's Progress}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1979 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1980 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:1970s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:1980s British comedy-drama television series]]\n[[Category:ITV television dramas]]\n[[Category:British comedy-drama television programmes]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n[[Category:Television programmes produced by Associated Television (ATV)]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n\n\n{{UK-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox television|\n  | show_name = Turtle's Progress\n  | image =\n  | runtime = 60 minutes\n  | creator = Edmund Ward\n  | producer = Nicholas Palmer\n  | starring  = [[John F. Landry]]<br>[[Michael Attwell]]<br>[[Paul Shane]]\n  | country = United Kingdom\n  | network = [[Associated TeleVision|ATV]] ([[ITV (TV network)|ITV]])\n  | first_aired = 23 April 1979\n  | last_aired = 4 July 1980\n  | num_episodes = 13\n  |}}\n\n'''''Turtle's Progress''''' is a [[British television]] series broadcast between 1979 and 1980.  The offbeat humour of the show attracted a small but cult audience, and the show only ran for two series.\n\n==Background==\nThe character of Turtle had first appeared in 1975 in \"[[The Hanged Man (TV series)|The Hanged Man]]\", also created by Edmund Ward.\n\n==Plot==\nThe series was an ITV ATV Drama, and dealt with a petty criminal named Turtle (played by [[John F. Landry]]) and his minder, \"Razor\" Eddie ([[Michael Attwell]]), who by accident come into possession of the proceeds of a major bank robbery. Eddie had been told to steal a van, and the van he stole turned out to be the getaway vehicle for the robbery. Inside were a large number of safe deposit boxes.\n\nEach episode of the show dealt with Turtle and Eddie opening one box and dealing with the contents of it.\n\nPart of the humour came from the interplay between Turtle and Superintendent Rafferty, who knew they did the crime, had no evidence on which to act, but lurked about in hope of a break.\n\nIn early 2011 the entire series was released on DVD by Networkdvd.co.uk.\n\n==Cast==\n[[John F. Landry]] - Turtle<br>\n[[Michael Attwell]] - Razor Eddie Malone<br>\nRuby Head - Aunt Ethel Wagstaff<br>\nTony London - George Wagstaff<br>\n[[James Grout]] - Superintendent Rafferty (Series 1 only)<br>\n[[David Swift (actor)|David Swift]] - Superintendent Rafferty (Series 2 only)<br>\n[[Tony Melody]] - Colour Sergeant Arnold<br>\n[[Leueen Willoughby]] - Miss Anthea Goodliff\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0078707|title=Turtle's Progress}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n[[Category:1979 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1980 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:1970s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:1980s British comedy-drama television series]]\n[[Category:ITV television dramas]]\n[[Category:British comedy-drama television programmes]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n[[Category:Television programmes produced by Associated Television (ATV)]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n\n{{UK-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turtle%27s_Progress"}
{"title_page": "Marit Tusvik", "text_new": "'''Marit Tusvik''' (born 13 March 1951, in [[H\u00f8yanger]]) is a [[Norway|Norwegian]] author, poet and playwright. Tusvik's works have been translated into multiple languages.<ref>[http://www.aschehougagency.no/authors/oktober/tusvik_marit Aschehoug summary]</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Reisa til mandarinlandet'' &ndash; poetry (1979)\n*''Mellom sol og m\u00e5ne'' &ndash; poetry (1984)\n*''I byen under byen'' &ndash; poetry (1985)\n*''Jorunn og Janfrid'' &ndash; children's book (1986)\n*''Hestehov'' &ndash; poetry (1987)\n*''Katrine'' &ndash; small book (1987)\n*''Kua som fraus'' &ndash; children's book  (1988)\n*''Bruno Andante og wobbegongen'' &ndash; children's book  (1989)\n*''Hareungen som blei \u00e5leine'' &ndash; children's book  (1990)\n*''Mugg'' &ndash; play (1990)\n*''Petter Larsens dag- og nattbok'' &ndash; children's book  (1991)\n*''Ishuset'' &ndash; novel (1991)<ref>In English \"The Ice House.\"</ref>\n*''Etter William'' &ndash; play (1993)\n*''Alle vakre jenters hambo'' &ndash; play (1994)<ref>In English \"All Beautiful Girls' Hambo.\"</ref>\n*''Kvalross i bikini'' &ndash; children's book (1994)\n*''Bell'' &ndash; novel (1995)\n*''H\u00f8rer du m\u00e5nen'' &ndash; film play (1996)\n*''Gjennomtrekk'' &ndash; poetry (1997)\n*''Barnas teaterbok'' &ndash; nonfiction for children (1997) (together with [[Jan E. Hansen]] & [[Mari Maurstad]])\n*''Tsaren'' &ndash; play (1998)\n*''Nord'' &ndash; novel (1999)\n*''Stille og fint'' &ndash; novel (2002)\n*''Proppen'' &ndash; children's book  (2002, illustrated by the author)\n*''Den forunderlige historia om Valdemar Bl\u00e5 og reisa gjennom havet'' &ndash; children's book  (2003, illustrated by the author)\n*''Angerh\u00f8y'' &ndash; play (2005)\n*''Sigrid Finne''&ndash; novel (2007)\n*''Samlede dikt''&ndash; poems (2008)\n\n==Prizes==\n*[[Sokneprest Alfred Andersson-Ryssts fund]] 1986\n*[[Ibsen Prize]] 1991\n*[[Nynorsk Literature Prize]] 1991\n*[[Mads Wiel Nygaards Endowment]] 1991\n*[[Narvesens kulturpris]] 1995\n*[[Amalie Skram-prisen]] 1999\n*[[Dobloug Prize]] 2004\n\n==References and notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.aschehougagency.no/authors/oktober/tusvik_marit Marit Tusvik]'s biography and bibliography at [http://www.aschehougagency.no/ Aschehoug Agency]\n\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Dobloug Prize winners}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tusvik, Marit}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dobloug Prize winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian poets]]\n[[Category:Norwegian children's writers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Norwegian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Norwegian poets]]\n[[Category:Norwegian women poets]]\n[[Category:Norwegian women novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Norwegian women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian women writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Marit Tusvik''' (born 13 March 1951, in [[H\u00f8yanger]]) is a [[Norway|Norwegian]] author, poet and playwright. Tusvik's works have been translated into multiple languages.<ref>[http://www.aschehougagency.no/authors/oktober/tusvik_marit Aschehoug summary]</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Reisa til mandarinlandet'' &ndash; poetry (1979)\n*''Mellom sol og m\u00e5ne'' &ndash; poetry (1984)\n*''I byen under byen'' &ndash; poetry (1985)\n*''Jorunn og Janfrid'' &ndash; children's book (1986)\n*''Hestehov'' &ndash; poetry (1987)\n*''Katrine'' &ndash; small book (1987)\n*''Kua som fraus'' &ndash; children's book  (1988)\n*''Bruno Andante og wobbegongen'' &ndash; children's book  (1989)\n*''Hareungen som blei \u00e5leine'' &ndash; children's book  (1990)\n*''Mugg'' &ndash; play (1990)\n*''Petter Larsens dag- og nattbok'' &ndash; children's book  (1991)\n*''Ishuset'' &ndash; novel (1991)<ref>In English \"The Ice House.\"</ref>\n*''Etter William'' &ndash; play (1993)\n*''Alle vakre jenters hambo'' &ndash; play (1994)<ref>In English \"All Beautiful Girls' Hambo.\"</ref>\n*''Kvalross i bikini'' &ndash; children's book (1994)\n*''Bell'' &ndash; novel (1995)\n*''H\u00f8rer du m\u00e5nen'' &ndash; film play (1996)\n*''Gjennomtrekk'' &ndash; poetry (1997)\n*''Barnas teaterbok'' &ndash; nonfiction for children (1997) (together with [[Jan E. Hansen]] & [[Mari Maurstad]])\n*''Tsaren'' &ndash; play (1998)\n*''Nord'' &ndash; novel (1999)\n*''Stille og fint'' &ndash; novel (2002)\n*''Proppen'' &ndash; children's book  (2002, illustrated by the author)\n*''Den forunderlige historia om Valdemar Bl\u00e5 og reisa gjennom havet'' &ndash; children's book  (2003, illustrated by the author)\n*''Angerh\u00f8y'' &ndash; play (2005)\n*''Sigrid Finne''&ndash; novel (2007)\n*''Samlede dikt''&ndash; poems (2008)\n\n==Prizes==\n*[[Sokneprest Alfred Andersson-Ryssts fund]] 1986\n*[[Ibsen Prize]] 1991\n*[[Nynorsk Literature Prize]] 1991\n*[[Mads Wiel Nygaards Endowment]] 1991\n*[[Narvesens kulturpris]] 1995\n*[[Amalie Skram-prisen]] 1999\n*[[Dobloug Prize]] 2004\n\n==References and notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.aschehougagency.no/authors/oktober/tusvik_marit Marit Tusvik]'s biography and bibliography at [http://www.aschehougagency.no/ Aschehoug Agency]\n\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{Dobloug Prize winners}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tusvik, Marit}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dobloug Prize winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian poets]]\n[[Category:Norwegian children's writers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Norwegian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Norwegian poets]]\n[[Category:Norwegian women poets]]\n[[Category:Norwegian women novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Norwegian women wr