{"title_page": "Tutu (plant)", "text_new": "[[File:Coriaria arborea tree tutu Te Anau 2.JPG|thumb|A ''Coriaria arborea'' tree (tutu)]]\n'''Tutu''' is a common name of [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] origin for plants in the genus ''[[Coriaria]]'' found in [[New Zealand]].\n\nSix New Zealand native species are known by the name:\n*''[[Coriaria angustissima]]''\n*''[[Coriaria arborea]]''\n*''[[Coriaria lurida]]''\n*''[[Coriaria plumosa]]''\n*''[[Coriaria pteridoides]]''\n*''[[Coriaria sarmentosa]]''\n\nThey are [[shrub]]s or [[tree]]s; some are [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] to New Zealand. Most of the plant parts are poisonous, containing the neurotoxin [[tutin (toxin)|tutin]] and its derivative hyenanchin. The widespread species ''[[Coriaria arborea]]'' is most often linked to cases of poisoning.<ref name=NZPCNCoriariaArborea>{{cite web|title=Coriaria arborea var. arborea|url=http://nzpcn.org.nz/flora_details.aspx?ID=1749|publisher=New Zealand Plant Conservation Network|accessdate=31 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Honey]] containing tutin can be produced by [[honey bee]]s feeding on [[honeydew (secretion)|honeydew]] produced by sap-sucking vine hopper insects (genus ''[[Scolypopa]]'') feeding on tutu.<ref>[http://www.nzfsa.govt.nz/animalproducts/publications/info-pamphlet/bee-products/toxic-honey.htm Background on toxic honey], New Zealand Food Safety Authority</ref> The last recorded deaths from eating honey containing tutin were in the 1890s,<ref name=\"NZ_Herald_10500105\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/food-wine/news/article.cfm?c_id=206&objectid=10500105 |title=Specialists expected tutin honey outbreak |author=Johnston, Martin |date=26 March 2008 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref> although sporadic outbreaks of [[toxic honey]] poisoning continue to occur.<ref name=\"Stuff.co.nz_1401506\">{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/1401506 |title=Four charges laid over toxic honey |author=Pepperell, Susan |date=15 February 2009 |work=[[The Sunday Star-Times]] |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref> Poisoning symptoms include delirium, vomiting, and coma.<ref name=\"Stuff.co.nz_2296984\">{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/2296984/ |title=Beekeeper to keep selling after poisoning |date=27 March 2009 |agency=[[NZPA]] |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the series 4 episode 3 of \"The Brokenwood Mysteries\" (2014), \"The Scarecrow\", the murder victim was killed by honey contaminated with tutin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.springfieldspringfield.co.uk/view_episode_scripts.php?tv-show=the-brokenwood-mysteries-2014&episode=s04e03|title=The Brokenwood Mysteries (2014) s04e03 Episode Script {{!}} SS|website=Springfield! Springfield!|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.teara.govt.nz/1966/T/Tutu/Tutu/en Tutu], 1966 Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Plant common name}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tutu (Plant)}}\n[[Category:Coriariaceae]]\n[[Category:Flora of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:M\u0101ori words and phrases]]\n\n\n{{Cucurbitales-stub}}\n{{NewZealand-plant-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Coriaria arborea tree tutu Te Anau 2.JPG|thumb|A ''Coriaria arborea'' tree (tutu)]]\n'''Tutu''' is a common name of [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] origin for plants in the genus ''[[Coriaria]]'' found in [[New Zealand]].\n\nSix New Zealand native species are known by the name:\n*''[[Coriaria angustissima]]''\n*''[[Coriaria arborea]]''\n*''[[Coriaria lurida]]''\n*''[[Coriaria plumosa]]''\n*''[[Coriaria pteridoides]]''\n*''[[Coriaria sarmentosa]]''\n\nThey are [[shrub]]s or [[tree]]s; some are [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] to New Zealand. Most of the plant parts are poisonous, containing the neurotoxin [[tutin (toxin)|tutin]] and its derivative hyenanchin. The widespread species ''[[Coriaria arborea]]'' is most often linked to cases of poisoning.<ref name=NZPCNCoriariaArborea>{{cite web|title=Coriaria arborea var. arborea|url=http://nzpcn.org.nz/flora_details.aspx?ID=1749|publisher=New Zealand Plant Conservation Network|accessdate=31 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Honey]] containing tutin can be produced by [[honey bee]]s feeding on [[honeydew (secretion)|honeydew]] produced by sap-sucking vine hopper insects (genus ''[[Scolypopa]]'') feeding on tutu.<ref>[http://www.nzfsa.govt.nz/animalproducts/publications/info-pamphlet/bee-products/toxic-honey.htm Background on toxic honey], New Zealand Food Safety Authority</ref> The last recorded deaths from eating honey containing tutin were in the 1890s,<ref name=\"NZ_Herald_10500105\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/food-wine/news/article.cfm?c_id=206&objectid=10500105 |title=Specialists expected tutin honey outbreak |author=Johnston, Martin |date=26 March 2008 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref> although sporadic outbreaks of [[toxic honey]] poisoning continue to occur.<ref name=\"Stuff.co.nz_1401506\">{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/1401506 |title=Four charges laid over toxic honey |author=Pepperell, Susan |date=15 February 2009 |work=[[The Sunday Star-Times]] |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref> Poisoning symptoms include delirium, vomiting, and coma.<ref name=\"Stuff.co.nz_2296984\">{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/2296984/ |title=Beekeeper to keep selling after poisoning |date=27 March 2009 |agency=[[NZPA]] |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the series 4 episode 3 of \"The Brokenwood Mysteries\" (2014), \"The Scarecrow\", the murder victim was killed by honey contaminated with tutin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.springfieldspringfield.co.uk/view_episode_scripts.php?tv-show=the-brokenwood-mysteries-2014&episode=s04e03|title=The Brokenwood Mysteries (2014) s04e03 Episode Script {{!}} SS|website=Springfield! Springfield!|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>  \n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.teara.govt.nz/1966/T/Tutu/Tutu/en Tutu], 1966 Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{Plant common name}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tutu (Plant)}}\n[[Category:Coriariaceae]]\n[[Category:Flora of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:M\u0101ori words and phrases]]\n\n\n{{Cucurbitales-stub}}\n{{NewZealand-plant-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tutu_(plant)"}
{"title_page": "Spencer Silver", "text_new": "retired American chemist who is big Shaq \nspecialized in adhesives. [[3M]] credits him with devising the adhesive that [[Arthur Fry|Art Fry]] used to create [[Post-it Note]]s.<ref name=\"3M\">{{cite web|title =About Post-it Brand |publisher=3M| url =http://www.post-it.com/wps/portal/3M/en_US/Post_It/Global/Home/About/About/ |accessdate =January 8, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"NIHF\">{{cite web |title=Inductees > Spencer Silver |url=https://www.invent.org/inductees/spencer-silver |website=National Inventors Hall of Fame |publisher=NIHF |accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nSilver was born in San Antonio, Texas. He majored in chemistry at [[Arizona State University]], earning a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] in 1962, then earned a doctorate in organic chemistry from the [[University of Colorado at Boulder]] in 1966, before taking a position as a Senior Chemist in 3M's Central Research Labs.<ref>{{cite web|title =Inventor of the Week Archive: Art Fry & Spencer Silver |publisher=MIT| url =http://web.mit.edu/invent/iow/frysilver.html4 |accessdate =January 8, 2011}}</ref> \n\nIn 1968, Silver developed a \"low-tack\" adhesive made of tiny acrylic spheres that would stick only where they were tangent to a given surface, rather than flat up against it. The adhesive's grip was strong enough to hold papers together, but weak enough to allow the papers to be pulled apart again without being torn. It could also be used again and again. The adhesive was patented in 1972 and described as suitable for use as a spray.<ref>{{cite web |title=US Patent 3691140A Acrylate copolymer microspheres |url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US3691140A/en |website=Google Patents |publisher=Google Inc |accessdate=October 24,  2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974 Art Fry attended an 3M internal seminar held by Spencer Silver, who was promoting the adhesive's properties. Fry regarded it as a potential solution to a practical challenge, that of preventing paper bookmarks from falling out of his hymnal when he sang in church. Fry developed bookmarks using Silver's adhesive, preventing them from leaving adhesive residue, and sought to interest others within the 3M company in them.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Meyer |first1=Nancy |title=Arthur Fry, Inventor of 3M\u2019s Post-it Note |url=https://wementor.com/2018/10/01/arthur-fry-inventor-of-3ms-post-it-note-part-i/ |website=WeMentor |publisher=WeMentor Inc |accessdate=October 24, 2019 |date=October 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Flavell-While |first1=Claudia |title=Spencer Silver and Arthur Fry: the chemist and the tinkerer who created the Post-it Note |url=https://www.thechemicalengineer.com/features/cewctw-spencer-silver-and-arthur-fry-in-search-of-an-application/ |website=The Chemical Engineer |publisher=Institution of Chemical Engineers |accessdate=October 25,  2019 |date=August 15, 2012}}</ref> The adhesive notes were initially marketed under the name Post 'n Peel in four cities from 1977 and as Post-it Notes from 1980 throughout the United States.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Duguid |first1=Sarah |title=First Person: \u2018We invented the Post-it Note\u2019 |url=https://www.ft.com/content/f08e8a9a-fcd7-11df-ae2d-00144feab49a |website=Financial Times |publisher=The Financial Times Ltd |date=December 3, 2010|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref> The product became very popular and has been sold worldwide since.  \n\nSilver worked at 3M until retiring in 1996. He is named in over 20 US patents. \n\nSpencer Silver has received several awards for his work, including the 1998 [[American Chemical Society]] Award for Creative Invention<ref>{{cite web |title=ACS Award for Creative Invention |url=https://www.acs.org/content/acs/en/funding-and-awards/awards/national/bytopic/acs-award-for-creative-invention.html |website=ACS |publisher=American Chemical Society |accessdate=October 25, 2019}}</ref> and induction into the [[National Inventors Hall of Fame]] in 2010.<ref name=\"NIHF\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Silver, Spencer}}\n[[Category:20th-century American chemists]]\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from San Antonio]]\n[[Category:Arizona State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Boulder alumni]]\n[[Category:3M people]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Texas]]\n[[Category:American inventors]]\n", "text_old": "'''Spencer Ferguson Silver''' (born February 6, 1941) is a retired American chemist who specialized in adhesives. [[3M]] credits him with devising the adhesive that [[Arthur Fry|Art Fry]] used to create [[Post-it Note]]s.<ref name=\"3M\">{{cite web|title =About Post-it Brand |publisher=3M| url =http://www.post-it.com/wps/portal/3M/en_US/Post_It/Global/Home/About/About/ |accessdate =January 8, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"NIHF\">{{cite web |title=Inductees > Spencer Silver |url=https://www.invent.org/inductees/spencer-silver |website=National Inventors Hall of Fame |publisher=NIHF |accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nSilver was born in San Antonio, Texas. He majored in chemistry at [[Arizona State University]], earning a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] in 1962, then earned a doctorate in organic chemistry from the [[University of Colorado at Boulder]] in 1966, before taking a position as a Senior Chemist in 3M's Central Research Labs.<ref>{{cite web|title =Inventor of the Week Archive: Art Fry & Spencer Silver |publisher=MIT| url =http://web.mit.edu/invent/iow/frysilver.html4 |accessdate =January 8, 2011}}</ref> \n\nIn 1968, Silver developed a \"low-tack\" adhesive made of tiny acrylic spheres that would stick only where they were tangent to a given surface, rather than flat up against it. The adhesive's grip was strong enough to hold papers together, but weak enough to allow the papers to be pulled apart again without being torn. It could also be used again and again. The adhesive was patented in 1972 and described as suitable for use as a spray.<ref>{{cite web |title=US Patent 3691140A Acrylate copolymer microspheres |url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US3691140A/en |website=Google Patents |publisher=Google Inc |accessdate=October 24,  2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974 Art Fry attended an 3M internal seminar held by Spencer Silver, who was promoting the adhesive's properties. Fry regarded it as a potential solution to a practical challenge, that of preventing paper bookmarks from falling out of his hymnal when he sang in church. Fry developed bookmarks using Silver's adhesive, preventing them from leaving adhesive residue, and sought to interest others within the 3M company in them.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Meyer |first1=Nancy |title=Arthur Fry, Inventor of 3M\u2019s Post-it Note |url=https://wementor.com/2018/10/01/arthur-fry-inventor-of-3ms-post-it-note-part-i/ |website=WeMentor |publisher=WeMentor Inc |accessdate=October 24, 2019 |date=October 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Flavell-While |first1=Claudia |title=Spencer Silver and Arthur Fry: the chemist and the tinkerer who created the Post-it Note |url=https://www.thechemicalengineer.com/features/cewctw-spencer-silver-and-arthur-fry-in-search-of-an-application/ |website=The Chemical Engineer |publisher=Institution of Chemical Engineers |accessdate=October 25,  2019 |date=August 15, 2012}}</ref> The adhesive notes were initially marketed under the name Post 'n Peel in four cities from 1977 and as Post-it Notes from 1980 throughout the United States.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Duguid |first1=Sarah |title=First Person: \u2018We invented the Post-it Note\u2019 |url=https://www.ft.com/content/f08e8a9a-fcd7-11df-ae2d-00144feab49a |website=Financial Times |publisher=The Financial Times Ltd |date=December 3, 2010|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref> The product became very popular and has been sold worldwide since.  \n\nSilver worked at 3M until retiring in 1996. He is named in over 20 US patents. \n\nSpencer Silver has received several awards for his work, including the 1998 [[American Chemical Society]] Award for Creative Invention<ref>{{cite web |title=ACS Award for Creative Invention |url=https://www.acs.org/content/acs/en/funding-and-awards/awards/national/bytopic/acs-award-for-creative-invention.html |website=ACS |publisher=American Chemical Society |accessdate=October 25, 2019}}</ref> and induction into the [[National Inventors Hall of Fame]] in 2010.<ref name=\"NIHF\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Silver, Spencer}}\n[[Category:20th-century American chemists]]\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from San Antonio]]\n[[Category:Arizona State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Boulder alumni]]\n[[Category:3M people]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Texas]]\n[[Category:American inventors]]\n", "name_user": "79.69.76.248", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spencer_Silver"}
