iled by Alan V. Murray, Institute for Medieval Studies, [[University of Leeds]]. Extensive and up to date as of 2004.\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{short description|Crusade from 1095 to 1099 that captured Jerusalem and established the Crusader States}}\n<!-- Interlanguage GAs and FAs -->\n\n<!-- Categories -->\n[[Category:First Crusade| ]]\n[[Category:11th-century crusades]]\n[[Category:1090s conflicts]]\n[[Category:History of Antioch]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Fatimid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Holy Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Republic of Genoa]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Republic of Pisa]]\n[[Category:Wars involving France]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Armenia]]\n[[Category:11th century in the Fatimid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:1090s in the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:1090s in Asia]]\n[[Category:1090s in Europe]]\n[[Category:1090s in the Kingdom of Jerusalem]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Crusade"}
{"title_page": "Ted Knight (politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n'''Edward Robert Knight''' (13 June 1933 \u2013 30 March 2020) was a local politician in [[London]], England, who was leader of [[Lambeth London Borough Council]] from 1978.<ref name=\"Ashley\">Cathy Ashley \"Ted Knight\" in Greg Rosen (ed.) ''Dictionary of Labour Biography'', London: Politicos, 2001, p.342-43</ref>\n\n==Lambeth Council==\nTed Knight was active in the Labour Party from a young age but was expelled from the Party in 1956 following a purge of the Trotskyist [[Workers' Revolutionary Party (UK)#Socialist Labour League|Socialist Labour League]] (SLL)<ref name=\"Ashley\"/>. Knight was re-admitted to the Norwood Constituency Labour Party in 1970, despite suspicions by some members that he retained his links with the proscribed SLL. In Norwood Labour Party Knight met [[Ken Livingstone]], later Leader of the [[Greater London Council]] and [[Mayor of London]], and the two formed an alliance to influence the selection of candidates in Norwood for the council elections in 1974. After that, they jostled for the leadership of the left within the Labour Group on Lambeth Borough Council but Livingstone's later move to Camden in North London left the way open for Knight to become the leading left-winger within the Labour Group and Leader of the Council.\n\nWhen the Conservative Government took powers through the [[Rates Act 1984]] to limit the budgets of local councils, several left-wing Labour councils organised a [[rate-capping rebellion|rebellion]] in which they refused to set a budget. All the councils eventually backed down except [[Liverpool City Council]] and Lambeth. The district auditor found that the council had lost interest on tax payments as a result, which was held to be due to the \"wilful misconduct\" of Knight and 31 other councillors. Each was required to repay the amount of lost interest in a surcharge and banned from holding office for five years. The Labour Party's leader, [[Neil Kinnock]], blamed local leaders like Ted Knight and [[Linda Bellos]] from Lambeth, for bringing the [[Labour Party UK|Labour Party]] into disrepute.\n\nPrior to the 1987 general election, Knight was a potential candidate for [[Coventry North East (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry North East]]: a runner-up at the [[Constituency Labour Party]] selection meeting, he lost out to [[John Hughes (Coventry North East MP)|John Hughes]].\n\n==After Lambeth==\nKnight took a break from politics after being expelled from office as a result of the [[Rate-capping rebellion]]. He pursued various business interests and remained treasurer of the town hall social club until it closed in 1994. He remained active within his union, [[Unite (trade union)|Unite]].\n\nKnight was elected to the National Committee of the [[Labour Representation Committee (2004)]] at their AGM on 17 November 2007. \n\nAfter the election of Jeremy Corbyn as leader of the Labour Party, Knight once again became active in Lambeth Labour, securing the post of Branch Chair in Gipsy Hill ward in November 2016.  \n\nKnight died in March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McDonnell |first1=John |title=A giant of our movement |url=https://www.john-mcdonnell.net/news/2020/03/30/a-giant-of-our-movement/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=John McDonnell MP |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite interview\n| last           =Knight\n| first          =Ted\n| interviewer    =Jeff Rodrigues\n| title          =Ted Knight interviewed by Jeff Rodrigues\n| url            =http://www.amielandmelburn.org.uk/collections/mt/pdf/81_01_11.pdf\n| format         =PDF\n| work           =[[Marxism Today]]\n| date           =January 1981\n\n| pages          =11&ndash;16\n| access-date    =2016-11-29\n| publisher      =[[Communist Party of Great Britain|CPGB]]\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knight, Ted}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Leaders of local authorities of England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n'''Edward Robert Knight''' (13 June 1933 \u2013 30 March 2020) was a local politician in [[London]], England who was leader of [[Lambeth London Borough Council]] from 1978.<ref name=\"Ashley\">Cathy Ashley \"Ted Knight\" in Greg Rosen (ed.) ''Dictionary of Labour Biography'', London: Politicos, 2001, p.342-43</ref>\n\n==Lambeth Council==\nTed Knight was active in the Labour Party from a young age but was expelled from the Party in 1956 following a purge of the Trotskyist [[Workers' Revolutionary Party (UK)#Socialist Labour League|Socialist Labour League]] (SLL)<ref name=\"Ashley\"/>. Knight was re-admitted to the Norwood Constituency Labour Party in 1970, despite suspicions by some members that he retained his links with the proscribed SLL. In Norwood Labour Party Knight met [[Ken Livingstone]], later Leader of the [[Greater London Council]] and [[Mayor of London]], and the two formed an alliance to influence the selection of candidates in Norwood for the council elections in 1974. After that, they jostled for the leadership of the left within the Labour Group on Lambeth Borough Council but Livingstone's later move to Camden in North London left the way open for Knight to become the leading left-winger within the Labour Group and Leader of the Council.\n\nWhen the Conservative Government took powers through the [[Rates Act 1984]] to limit the budgets of local councils, several left-wing Labour councils organised a [[rate-capping rebellion|rebellion]] in which they refused to set a budget. All the councils eventually backed down except [[Liverpool City Council]] and Lambeth. The district auditor found that the council had lost interest on tax payments as a result, which was held to be due to the \"wilful misconduct\" of Knight and 31 other councillors. Each was required to repay the amount of lost interest in a surcharge and banned from holding office for five years. The Labour Party's leader, [[Neil Kinnock]], blamed local leaders like Ted Knight and [[Linda Bellos]] from Lambeth, for bringing the [[Labour Party UK|Labour Party]] into disrepute.\n\nPrior to the 1987 general election, Knight was a potential candidate for [[Coventry North East (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry North East]]: a runner-up at the [[Constituency Labour Party]] selection meeting, he lost out to [[John Hughes (Coventry North East MP)|John Hughes]].\n\n==After Lambeth==\nKnight took a break from politics after being expelled from office as a result of the [[Rate-capping rebellion]]. He pursued various business interests and remained treasurer of the town hall social club until it closed in 1994. He remained active within his union, [[Unite (trade union)|Unite]].\n\nKnight was elected to the National Committee of the [[Labour Representation Committee (2004)]] at their AGM on 17 November 2007. \n\nAfter the election of Jeremy Corbyn as leader of the Labour Party, Knight once again became active in Lambeth Labour, securing the post of Branch Chair in Gipsy Hill ward in November 2016.  \n\nKnight died in March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McDonnell |first1=John |title=A giant of our movement |url=https://www.john-mcdonnell.net/news/2020/03/30/a-giant-of-our-movement/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=John McDonnell MP |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite interview\n| last           =Knight\n| first          =Ted\n| interviewer    =Jeff Rodrigues\n| title          =Ted Knight interviewed by Jeff Rodrigues\n| url            =http://www.amielandmelburn.org.uk/collections/mt/pdf/81_01_11.pdf\n| format         =PDF\n| work           =[[Marxism Today]]\n| date           =January 1981\n\n| pages          =11&ndash;16\n| access-date    =2016-11-29\n| publisher      =[[Communist Party of Great Britain|CPGB]]\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knight, Ted}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Leaders of local authorities of England]]\n", "name_user": "Deb", "label": "safe", "comment": "punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ted_Knight_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "Sinan Tuzcu", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Sinan Tuzcu\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1977|7|10}}\n| birth_place  = [[Gaziantep]], [[Turkey]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| occupation   = Actor\n| yearsactive  =\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Dolunay Soysert]]|2006|2016|reason=div}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/dolunay-soysert-ile-sinan-tuzcu-bosandi-40163775|title=Dolunay Soysert ile Sinan Tuzcu bo\u015fand\u0131|work=H\u00fcrriyet|date=23 July 2016|accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Sinan Tuzcu''' (born 10 July 1977) is a [[Turkish people|Turkish]] actor.\n\n==Biography==\nAfter doing a course on Tourism and Hotel Management at [[Bilkent University]], he graduated in Theatre from [[Mimar Sinan Fine Arts University|Mimar Sinan University]]'s State Conservatory in 2003. Tuzcu who had previously worked part-time at the Ankara State Theatre, began acting professionally at the Bilkent Drama Studio.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nTuzcu was married to actress [[Dolunay Soysert]] from 2006 to 2016.\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[\u0130n\u015faat]]'' (2003)\n*''[[The Net 2.0]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Ihlamurlar Alt\u0131nda]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Kabuslar Evi: Seni Beklerken]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Pazar - Bir Ticaret Masal\u0131]]'' (2007)\n*''[[\u00c7emberin D\u0131\u015f\u0131nda]]'' (2007)\n*''[[Mavi G\u00f6zl\u00fc Dev]]'' (2007)\n*''[[Elveda Rumeli]]'' (2007\u20132008)\n*''[[Adanal\u0131]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Nefes]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Alt\u0131n K\u0131zlar]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Orada]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Yol Arkada\u015f\u0131m]]'' (2008\u20132009)\n*''[[Ask ve Ceza]]'' (2009\u20132010)\n*''[[Veda (film)|Veda]]'' (2010)\n*''G\u00f6r\u00fc\u015f G\u00fcn\u00fc Kad\u0131nlar\u0131'' (2013)\n*''A\u015fk Ekmek Hayaller'' (2013)\n*''Urfal\u0131yam Ezelden'' (2014; writer)\n*''[[Kaderimin Yaz\u0131ld\u0131\u011f\u0131 G\u00fcn]]'' (2014\u20132015)\n*''Kehribar'' (2016; writer)\n*''Saruhan'' (2016)\n*''[[Arka Sokaklar]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Sen Anlat Karadeniz]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|2118133|Sinan Tuzcu}}\n* [http://www.sinematurk.com/kisi/8156/Sinan-Tuzcu Sinan Tuzcu ~ SinemaT\u00fcrk]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tuzcu, Sinan}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Gaziantep]]\n[[Category:Turkish male film actors]]\n[[Category:Turkish male television actors]]\n[[Category:Turkish male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Mimar Sinan Fine Arts University alumni]]\n\n\n{{Turkey-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Sinan Tuzcu\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1977|7|10}}\n| birth_place  = [[Gaziantep]], [[Turkey]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| occupation   = Actor\n| yearsactive  =\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Dolunay Soysert]]|2006|2016|reason=div}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/dolunay-soysert-ile-sinan-tuzcu-bosandi-40163775|title=Dolunay Soysert ile Sinan Tuzcu bo\u015fand\u0131|work=H\u00fcrriyet|date=23 July 2016|accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Sinan Tuzcu''' (born 10 July 1977) is a [[Turkish people|Turkish]] actor.\n\n==Biography==\nAfter doing a course on Tourism and Hotel Management at [[Bilkent University]], he graduated in Theatre from [[Mimar Sinan Fine Arts University|Mimar Sinan University]]'s State Conservatory in 2003. Tuzcu who had previously worked part-time at the Ankara State Theatre, began acting professionally at the Bilkent Drama Studio.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\nTuzcu was married to actress [[Dolunay Soysert]] from 2006 to 2016.\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[\u0130n\u015faat]]'' (2003)\n*''[[The Net 2.0]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Ihlamurlar Alt\u0131nda]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Kabuslar Evi: Seni Beklerken]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Pazar - Bir Ticaret Masal\u0131]]'' (2007)\n*''[[\u00c7emberin D\u0131\u015f\u0